How travel prices have changed since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered travel mainly in the countries of the socialist bloc, because travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for holiday in East Germany, Soviet Union (Sotchi, Crimea and Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A great exception for the period 1962 to 1972 when he was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then the regime began to have a tendency for the west and travels to Yugoslavia were very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not permitted for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the socialist countries.
In the case where the Czech Republic wanted to travel individually, for example in Poland or the Soviet Union, it was necessary that a letter of invitation be sent to the Czech Republic if the individual travel was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered to travel to the West, however it was necessary to make the tail all night with a sleeping bag or to have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that, it wasn't won yet.
The agreement for currencies that was the condition to travel west was refused to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
However, the Czechoslovak currency was not interchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the currency agreement (western currency) to travel west.
The Czechs spent most of their vacations in the country where there were, therefore, many homes of campaign and chalets that the Czechs had bought, and this habit is still hard.
Since 1989 the Czech travels have seen a great revolution.
Although up until 1989 the holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were maximum, last year the Czechs spent 4 million days abroad in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we do not know today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because part of Yugoslavia of the time.
The removal of visas in the 1990s in the neighbouring countries of the West caused a huge wave of short-term visits mainly in Austria in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not travel by plane to the west for a long time that everyone wanted to see for at least one moment.
For example, in Paris travel organizations slept the Czechs in tents in parks because our income did not allow us to pay the hotel or a pension.
The typical trade of a Czech trip was at this time to bring with it its own preserved food, sauces, etc... to save.
Another important moment has also been the exchangeability of the Czech crown which has allowed our tourists finally after decades of free purchase of Western currency.
Our standard of living as well as the average wage increased what led to another important moment around 1997.
As a result of a growing demand for travel, travel agencies have been preparing tours with air charter connections since 1997 that have greatly reduced the costs compared to what was before.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs had unintended connections with practically most of the developed countries around the world outside the EU, which later facilitated our journeys.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter was prepared for an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic.
Since this year, as every year of direct air charters take Czech tourists to the distant warm countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
