An analysis of the possibility of a "vote by vote" count in Michoacán
According to the data provided by PREP, the difference between the first and second seats of the governor's election is only 27 per cent, even without accounting for the votes corresponding to 879 out of the 6 thousand 74 total verbatim records.
The "vote by vote" bill is a reality for the electoral process this year in Michoacán, where according to the data provided by the Preliminary Electoral Results Programme (PREP) the difference between the first and second seats of the governor's election is only 27 per cent, even without accounting for the votes corresponding to the 879 out of the 6 thousand 74 total verbatim records.
In this regard, the President of the General Council of the Michoacán Electoral Institute (IMM), María de los Llandales Zaragoza, recalled that a number of days ago, last November 9, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines to harmonise local standards for federal electoral reform.
It will be recalled that Michoacán has not approved either its Political Constitution or its Electoral Code or the Electoral Justice Act, at the same time that the Congress of the State approved the reforms shortly before the end of the legal period so that this electoral process can enter into force and Governor Leonel Godoy Range has omitted its publication within the time limits provided by the Official Journal of the State Act, with the argument that he had some objections.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional dispute promoted by the Local Legislative Power and qualified as "invalid and illegal" the vote of the State Ombudsman for constitutional reforms, because he did not have the right to "sanction or challenge them".
Interviewed on the possibility of "vote by vote", María de los Ángeles Llandal said that through the approval of the relevant guidelines by the IEM General Council it will be possible to complete the partial and total vote by the local electoral body.
Thus, the partial counting of votes, of one or more electoral packages, may be: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no record of vote and the minutes are not counted in the minutes file at the chairman's office; or there are obvious errors or alterations in the minutes.
In addition, the total count of votes received in all polling sessions may be made when there is an indication that the difference between the alleged candidate winning the respective election and the person who received the second place in the poll is equal or below a percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express petition from the party representative and/or coalition who presented the second of the candidates reported.
The total voter count may also be made if at the end of the joint count it is that the difference between the alleged winning candidate and the second-ranking candidate is equal to or less than a percentage point, provided that there is an express petition from the political party to whom the second candidate has been issued, in which case the electoral packages that have been the subject of the partial count will be excluded.
It should be noted that this is the situation of the election of Morelia, where according to the PRSP, the difference between the first and second seats is only 0.16 per cent, even without accounting for the votes of 129 of the 923 total verbatim records.
