MSS announces protocol to find the gene of obesity
Social insurance conducts an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in the case of children and young people; this is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) announced that it conducts an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people, called the 'Genetic Protocol of Child and Teen obesity' which will allow the markers associated with overweight.
In a communiqué, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital des Specialités du Centro Nationale Constituent du 20th Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of physicians, nurses, nutritionists and social assistants had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and third-cycle students of the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the investigation, the population with or without the right to participate is invited to present themselves to the participating sports units of the IMSS in Valle de México, where the evidence is provided to minors every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (State of Mexico Poniente) and that from 8 October, the activity took place in the Sports Unit of Nezahualcoyolt (State of Mexico East).
After meeting 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Independent Sports Unit (South of Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (North of Federal District).
He explained that the objective of this investigation and that it was aware of the components and importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors for children and young Mexicans in order to prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
As the World Diabetes Day was to be celebrated on 14 November, he noted that the goal was to gather three thousand children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and under the supervision of their parents, for the implementation of specific food-related questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and past family heritage of their diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that cause such disorders as diabetes or renal impairment.
It detailed that Saturdays will be applied to all participants in anthropometric measurements (weight, size, circumference of the size), blood pressure, glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetics (researched to identify people associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming weighting in the case of minors.
'The health surveys of 1999 and 2006 indicated that in only six years there was an increase of 77 per cent in obesity in boys and 47 per cent in girls; in the case of overweight there was also a dramatic increase', the IMSS specialist stressed.
He noted that the justification for the search for markers was based on the fact that the population of the country was different from others in its genetic history.
He reported that on average, Mexicans have 65 percent of Indo-American heritage, 30 percent European and five percent African, and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that, in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy consumed (calorie), which is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the full assessment of children, which allows them to detect whether they are overweight or obesity.
It even says that the presence of more dark color (anthosis) on the neck and front arms indicates the likelihood of metabolic and even prediabetic alterations.
The information is managed in a confidential manner, and doctors provide it in writing to parents, to whom each of the measures and changes in the lifestyle they need to make in order to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic disorders: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, stay most of the day sitting in front of the TV and use transport means instead of walking on short distances.
Another cause is the high caloric intake, i.e. the largest consumption of sugar drinks, carbohydrates (tamals - meat pulp of corn flour wrapped in corn leaves - bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and genetics analysed in this protocol.
UNAM's asphalt would avoid cassis
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of the environmental and temperature conditions.
If the signals that the paving were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair approximately 200 thousand cassis each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of Valle de México, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry (FQ), who has ensured that if the building and maintenance process of the bituminous pare is adequate, the cassis could be reduced or even eliminated completely.
During his conference A technological opinion on cassis, organized within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory responsible for developing asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture having similar characteristics to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera considered that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, like some cities in the north, to improve performance, and therefore the formation of cassis.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbons molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphalt, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called malthen, which together give the pope its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, almost 180 degrees, behaves as a liquid, at 120 degrees C, its viscosity is very large and at 50 degrees C it presents an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes falling, it adds.
This means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, the chemical engineering specialist warns.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City were mostly covered by a flexible paving, consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which involved asphalt.
Among the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and subsequently compacted.
Each of the small stones that form the bed, signal, is bathed an asphalt.
When vehicles pass through it by generating efforts, it allows the forces to spread very well in the paving.
If the asphalt had been modified, the asphalt would be better spread, in the opinion of the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt layer, he said, a last layer called asphalt layer, made of fine stone, i.e. sand, which is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the layer of asphalt and provide adhesion in the street.
As part of the paving that receives and distributes the effort, the rolling layer also requires that the paving layer has an adequate thickness and the material it is made must be treated.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, is also a very important factor to consider, especially water, because they significantly affect the performance of the asphalt layer.
When the soil wets, the water spreads inside the layer it is difficult for it to be so, which brings together all the layers of the pail and therefore causes the cassis.
In the process of formation of a case, he said, the first to go is the rolling film and only later the asphalt layer is affected, but the damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that must be treated to the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National Research System explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor for case formation and therefore the thickness of each layer of the paddle must always be linked to the load of vehicles and ensure its satisfaction, in order to avoid frequent case formation.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bitumen emulsions, which already exist on the market in other countries and allow for easy repair of the case without having to use high temperatures.
