The North Stream, new entry door for Russian gas in Europe
The North Stream gas pipeline, directly linking Western Europe to Russia by going to the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has entered into service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with burst.
More than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, took part on Tuesday on the Baltic coasts, between orchestra and buffet, at the inauguration of the North Stream, this new gas pipeline that directly connects Russia to Germany under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart of the Netherlands Mark Rutte turned together the wheel of the valve leading the entry of the Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas will reach every year in Western Europe by a first tube of 1,224 km related to the region of Saint Petersburg in the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerian.
A second tube is due to be completed at the end of 2012, allowing to deliver a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, the equivalent of all French consumption.
The possibility of building a third on the same route is already mentioned.
For Gazprom, the completion in time and time of this huge construction has victory airs.
The project had been strongly challenged by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The North Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose a little of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets.
As far as the debate is concerned, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare North Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact ", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is whether the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But it is at the price of a weakening Europe of energy, as the project created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has, in five years' time, triumphed over its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, highly gas-consumers, whose deposits are declining.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us organically," said François Fillon, inaugurating this pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which large gas contracts are both political and economic.
All of this explains the broad smiles shown by the Gazprom leaders, present in number in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical plant.
The underwater tube is made of concrete steel to protect it from the anchors of ships.
It is located on the bottom of the sea, 200 m on average.
In order to build it, it was necessary to avoid areas of mines dating from World War II.
" One hundred had to be removed or destroyed by caution," says Jens Müller, spokesperson for Nord Stream.
There was also a need to multiply measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, which doesn't stop at all its length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned outside Sweden, but the project was rejected by the Swedish authorities, while the Swedish were not willing to see a Russian state company permanently established across their coasts.
"In case of emergency, we stop the gas passage in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of escape, the gas contained in the gas pipeline thus escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builders who have planned the dives to know a escape every 100,000 years.
The monitoring of the state of the gas pipeline is ensured by a submarine robot, trained by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an apparatus circulating inside the gas pipeline.
In the form of a cigarette, it is inserted inside the tube, wide with a diameter of one metre, and it is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at the speed of 3 meters second, it provides detailed information on any deformation of the metal.
The gas pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without having to undergo the least repair.
Gas flow is simply secured by pressure.
It is 200 bars away, and 100 bars on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
The Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each), joined.
These five companies created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the gas pipeline.
It has its seat in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented to this company, for 20 years renewable, the total capacity of gas transport.
" Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
Funding for the construction of the pipeline was made up of 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work should be EUR 7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to return to their expenses, since only Gazprom takes the risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy side planted with pines.
Valves, heights of 4.5 meters, form the gas outlet.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that occurs before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since Tuesday, this terminal has received a million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour.
With full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
