Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th week for the employment of persons with disabilities is open today.
Despite a voluntary public policy in 2005, the unemployment rate of persons with disabilities is twice as high as the average: 19%, compared to 9% for the entire population.
Discouragement?
“No,” said Éric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, “the association that organizes the week for the employment of persons with disabilities.”
" Progress made for fifteen years has been considerable. "
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher."
" Nevertheless, it still remains enormous to do."
It must be said that for disabled unemployed people, obstacles remain many before access to employment.
They are older than they are: 37% are over 50 years of age (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have the bacca and of the 2.3 million higher education students, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
In short, so many criteria that specifically complicate the return to employment and that "are the core of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help businesses recruit disabled workers.
That's for the target brakes.
It remains the non-dit, the mentalities that evolve, of course, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Enterprise Association for the City indicated that interrogated managers have " a low level of knowledge of the disability " , with a " overrepresentation of wheelchairs, mental or intellectual disabilities " .
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the employment goal of 6% of disabled workers, set out in a law of 1987.
The last known figures, dating from 2008, account for a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," said Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The evidence: the number of " taxed " institutions, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59 000 to 46 000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
" The 2005 Act, which increased contributions, created a strong pressure on businesses," explains Pierre Blanc.
" But this improvement also translates a real awareness, especially in large groups. "
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of the institutions of 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of the enterprises of 100 to 199 employees.
